# **1\.  Introduction** {#1.-introduction}

## 

## **1.1  Purpose** {#1.1-purpose}

The purpose of this document is to provide a high-level architecture representation of BBVA’s Ether Workplace Platform.

## **1.2  Scope** {#1.2-scope}

This document encompasses most significant components included in the Ether Workplace layer. The remaining Ether Platform subsystems (PaaS, DaaS, IaaS, SEMaaS, etc.) will be referenced when applicable but will not be addressed.

## 

## **1.3  Intended Audience** {#1.3-intended-audience}

This document is targeted at readers who need to understand the component parts of a specific discipline in the platform. Intended audience includes  IT executives and non-technical resources. While diagrams and component definitions must employ a certain amount of technical terminology, this deliverable is intended for its use and understanding by teams at all levels.

For high level definitions of technical terms, a glossary is available for reference in the following [link](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1ulDIbrXsl_GVS6DH9LeL4hbDKQL_ay693S2optuhXQc).

## 

## **1.4  Overview** {#1.4-overview}

This document’s main concern is to address Ether’s Workplace architecture documentation. It will have a static view which identifies the most significant components with their purpose, responsibilities and the relationships between them.

# **2\.  Workplace Architectural Overview** {#2.-workplace-architectural-overview}

## 

## **2.1  What is Workplace** {#2.1-what-is-workplace}

Workplace refers to the set of tools a standard employee across all geographies needs to carry out his/her everyday job. 

![][image1]

## 

## 

## **2.2  Workplace Objective** {#2.2-workplace-objective}

Workplace has been created to provide BBVA Group with a new set of tools that will offer the possibility to improve both workplace customer experience and security as well as reduce operational costs.

![][image2]

## **2.3 Workplace Context (as is)** {#2.3-workplace-context-(as-is)}

User experience around Workplace in BBVA has recently not been as good as expected because

 of four main troubles.

* Unclear Workplace Strategy  
* Lack of a Governance structure  
* No end-to-end customer experience processes vision  
* Siloed Technological approach to take decisions

There has been a lack of awareness about internal customer experience and its impact on employees’ productivity: Workplace has never been part of BBVA strategic agenda

After an initial assessment done locally in each country these are the conclusions.

At the enabling level, Workplace function is managed without a strategic perspective that does not consider users actual needs

![][image3]

## 

At the Operating level, examining each Workplace Building Block, main issues are found for UX and deficient equipment and support.

![][image4]

When examining the maturity stage of each process at global level, significant issues have been found for three of them

![][image5]

## 

## 

## **2.4 Workplace strategy and product oriented organization** {#2.4-workplace-strategy-and-product-oriented-organization}

To address the problems that were discovered in the initial assessment Workplace has defined a strategy based on 6 strategic principles  
**![][image6]**

Based on these principles we are organized into products. These products pursue excellence in their field of reference but a coordination layer maintains coherence and pursue some global transformation objectives[^1]

### **Workplace Products aspirations** {#workplace-products-aspirations}

BBVA @Connect aspiration is to provide seamless and secure global connection to fast and integrated networks across geographies and BUs

BBVA @Collaborate aspiration is to provide global, simple, user friendly collaboration tools, integrated with existing infrastructure

BBVA @Communicate aspiration is to provide global ‘self-served’ communications that are integrated across geographies and BUs

BBVA @Work aspiration is to provide end-users with secure devices, tools and technical support they need to perform their job

BBVA @Security aspiration is to provide secure access to data, devices, networks and communications in a workplace environment.

BBVA @Employee aspiration is to ensure all workplace products provide a pleasant end-to-end user experience and that a fluent communication channel is established between IT and employees.

This is a functional schema of Workplace to better see all Workplace’s domain:

![][image7]

## 

## **2.5  Workplace Roles** {#2.5-workplace-roles}

	**Product Owner**

Responsible for coordinating  the definition, maintenance and evolution of each Workplace product .  

We’re divide into 6 products[^2]: @Connect, @Collaborate @Communicate @Work @Security and @Employee

**Product Specialist**  
Provide specialist knowledge and expertise on key technologies that are to be implemented in each of the Workplace products, based on latest trends and best practices

**Strategy manager**  
Lead data insights that help drive strategic and tactical decisions.  
Identify new kinds, types and sources of data to drive product innovation

**Security Specialist**  
Guarantee all workplace products are compliant with the security norms.

**UX manager**  
Supervise end-to-end processes where users interact with technology ensuring a smooth and pleasant user experience

**Local workplace architect**  
They’re workplace eyes and ears in each country. They’re responsible to listen to local employees and raise their voice to ask product managers to include new features to solve their problems.  
They define Workplace policies, standards and guidelines for local Workplace products, with focus on user experience excellence and following global recommendations and guidelines  
Ensure and coordinate the evolution of local Workplace products   
Ensure deployment of global initiatives.

# **3\.  Product Description** {#3.-product-description}

## **3.1  @Connect** {#3.1-@connect}

BBVA @Connect aspiration is to provide seamless and secure global connection to fast and integrated networks across geographies and BUs

User expectations:

* One unique and integrated network (WiFi, LAN…) for all BBVA Business Units and geographies across the world

* Simple but secure and fluid access to corporate data and applications inside and outside the office

* Single authentication (no double registry) for devices and networks, providing transparent security for the user

* Internet always available to access corporate sites and to use any service with the required quality level

![][image8]

### 

### **@Connect Workplace trends identified** {#@connect-workplace-trends-identified}

* Risk management, security analytics and end user security awareness will most probably need to compensate the decreasing control ability of IT organizations as the “deny by default” paradigm grows outdated

* Integrate network access control (NAC) policy servers with ATD (Anti Threat Detection) solutions to share contextual information (for example, user identity and device info), so that security operations teams will have information that will enable them to shorten the incident response window.

* Increasing adoption of a more mobile, social, data-driven and consumer like workplace for corporate users

* Network Access technologies will be coupled with threat intelligence and network visibility for enhanced protection

* Critical infrastructure industries will use incumbent IoT authentication methods to upgrade to a more secure approach for device authentication

* Organizations will adopt new biometric authentication methods (such as face, iris and voice recognition) offered by device and OS manufacturers, in conjunction with contextual attributes for effective remote workforce authentication.

###  **Our approach: Conceptual solution** {#our-approach:-conceptual-solution}

![][image9]

**Users**

* Enhance the user's management unifying the user's repositories (AD forest, virtual directories, among others) to reduce complexity

* Role- based access model to apply security access controls needs 

* Provide SSO capabilities to any user in any channel to enhance the user experience.

**Devices**

* Implement Adaptive authentication controls in order to provide strong authentication factors when applicable	

* Unified workplace authentication and authorization policies in a single repository to cover the different user access methods  

* Analyze next generation of NAC vision and capabilities 

**Services**

* Provide Enterprise Single Sign-On services for seamless authentication in applications out of the scope of current SSO

* Provide a secure remote access to internal networks and to internet

* Offer access to internal resources over BBVA Wifi.

**![][image10]**  
@Connect conceptual architecture model

## **3.2  @Communicate** {#3.2-@communicate}

BBVA @Communicate aspiration is to provide global and  ‘self-served’ communications that are integrated across geographies and BUs

User expectations:

* Fully integrated and compatible communication between employees transparent for the user

* Users can communicate from any corporate device, anywhere in the world

* Latest communication tools and devices are leveraged to enable different communication requirements

* Employees can communicate with each other, with customers or with providers in real-time with an appropriate quality level

### **Market and Customers Trends**  {#market-and-customers-trends}

**Seamless Communication**

Powerful collaboration tools have emerged to seamlessly connect individuals and companies.  They enable high-performance teamwork, and…

* Unified Interface . Access telephony, email, voicemail, IM, conferencing, and document sharing from one interface 

* Accessibility. Locate, connect and collaborate with others seamlessly and instantaneously regardless of one’s location and available communication device

Erase the lines of geography and corporate boundaries enabling the workforce to collaborate as if in the same room

* Natural Human Interaction. Increase executive interaction and impact, with less travel and reduced corporate carbon-footprint

* Workgroup Collaboration. Teams work together more effectively by obtaining the visual elements of communications

**As a Service Solutions**                         

* The market is moving toward an As-a-Service delivery model that provides plug-in, scalable, consumption-based business services that deliver the business outcomes that every organization demands—increased revenue or decreased costs. 

**Suite Completeness Capabilities (To be)**

Strong, centralized and consistent communicate environment consolidating, standardizing and centralizing operations.

* Unique Tool

* Maximizing capabilities and Minimizing integrations with third parties

* Simplifying technology roadmap

* Improvement of User Experience

* Reduce Operating costs

* Consolidate, standardize and centralize operations

### **Reference architecture**  {#reference-architecture}

Understood as a whole Architecture providing Seamless and Integrated Capabilities.

The Audio and Video capabilities has to be reviewed as  a whole integrated solution more than of pure “video conferencing capabilities, integrated in a seamless communication experience for the final user as following conceptual model indicates:

![][image11]

**Telcos & Cloud Services**

The Framework shows in a nutshell, an integrated three layer model to build an end-to-end global communication architecture, from the end-user to the pure traditional telephony or mobile 3G service / 4G, up to a full service in the cloud, like the collaboration suite where the email is just one more component, virtual meeting services or additional integration services to complement the first ones.

**Voice GW**

From a functional point of view the first building block is the portion of the solution to access to the public switched telephone network (PSTN dial-tone). The voice currently is part of the IP data in the WAN, the access to the PSTN has been centralized through gateways at the local premises mainly in the DC.

**IPT & Audio Video**

These functional blocks are responsible the set of infrastructure on premises, for IP telephony, and Videoconferencing and Telepresence services (meeting rooms immersive) including all the endpoints of users and specific equipment in the meeting rooms.

**IM, Virtual Meeting & Federation**

The Instant Messaging tools are evolving from a pure P2P communicate to a complete suite integrating many endpoints to the meeting  and to be federated with main partners. The functional split of this three communications tools aims to introduce a set of requirements and recommendations on how the current limitations can be addressed.

**Users & devices**

The final device is the point of contact with the user. User's role differentiation and device diversity are the key to ensure a user experience according to the expectation of each of user groups and how they are consuming network It services.

## **3.3 @Collaborate** {#3.3-@collaborate}

BBVA @Collaborate aspiration is to provide global, simple, user friendly collaboration tools, integrated with existing infrastructure

These are the user expectations:

* Users are enabled to efficiently and securely collaborate with their teams, customers and partners

* Users can collaborate from any corporate device,anytime and anywhere in the world.

* Collaboration tools are integrated across geographies and BUs, enabling seamless collaboration experiences

* Users can choose the best collaboration channel to suit their needs (share content, communicate…)

* Integration between communication and collaboration tools

**Social Network**

Google+ is available as *out of the box* solution but with not wide extended use as no adopting plan has been performed.

**People**

Some users have fill their owns profiles in G+. It’s not mandatory.

**Team Sites**

Google Site is widely used

Google Drive is being adopted

**Knowledge Exchange**

**Publishing and Internal Apps**

### **Covering current gaps with solutions included in Google Suite:** {#covering-current-gaps-with-solutions-included-in-google-suite:}

Use of Google Sites to build new capabilities around social networks like Team Sites, Ideas, Knowledge Exchange or Blog.

Use of Google Groups for Business to allow new ways of collaboration.

Use of Google Drive instead of Google Sites to share information

Use of Google+ to build new capabilities around social networks (People to allow Knowledge Sharing and Find People).

![][image12]

Our recommendation is to maintain Google for foundational collaboration capabilities

Enforce current Document Sharing capabilities of Google as a pillar point for social capabilities enhancements.

- Google Drive / Team Drives  
- Google Sites

Include new tools as Inbox, Keep to increase personal productivity.

Explore CISCO collaboration/communications tools integration as Spark.

### **Endpoint Framework** {#endpoint-framework}

This framework defines the elements that must be considered in the design, implementation and deployment of any current or future device for our digital workplace in BBVA:

![][image19]

All these elements interact between them in specific ways. This framework is an allocation of functions and responsibilities and not a rigid approach:

* User Experience: any particular element, regarding human-device interaction, whose outcome is a positive or negative perception of the endpoint. It comprises both hard (hardware, software, visuals, accessibility, etc) and soft (emotions, feelings, trustworthiness, etc) factors.  
* Core functions:  
  * Hardware: Device & Peripherals. Physical components used to digital information processing. More specifically, Endpoints are digital devices with human-computer interface, computing processing and both volatile and nonvolatile memory.  
  * Connectivity. Networks and their access points that devices use to communicate with other devices, inside and, potentially, outside the corporate scope (Internet).  
  * Operating System. Software component that manages endpoint hardware and software resources, providing common services for programs. All software programs, except firmware, require an operating system to function.  
  * Roles: Users & Groups. Users, as individual personas, or groups of users with common needs and access permissions.  
  * Applications. Software components which fulfills specific business requirements.  
  * Data. Information managed by users or groups of users using applications on their workplace devices.  
* Cross responsibilities:  
  * Security: any possible element devoted to ensure proper access to the endpoint and its components.  
  * Support: services and tools devoted to help users in their day-to-day endpoint use, and specifically in requests and issues.  
  * Management: services and tools dedicated to ensure proper level of service of every endpoint, including both administration and operation.  
  * Economics: any activity or component aim at managing required resources (financial budget, purchase/renting processes, human workforce, etc)  for design, implement, deliver and deploy endpoints to final users.

Different framework flavours have been developed for each technical platform in use in the organization:

* Microsoft Windows endpoint framework.  
* Apple macOs endpoint framework.  
* Linux desktop endpoint framework.  
* Mobile (Android, iOS) endpoint framework.

A list of Endpoint Security Requirements have been defined for all these four platforms.

## **3.5 @Security**   {#3.5-@security}

From Security Architecture, workplace initiatives are evaluated based on a security framework that contains:

* **Access control**: In information technology, (logical) access controls are tools and protocols used for identification, authentication, authorization, and accountability in computer information systems.

* **Operation security & Cryptography:** is a process that identifies critical information to determine if friendly actions can be observed by cybercriminal intelligence, determines if information obtained by cybercriminal could be interpreted to be useful to them, and then executes selected measures that eliminate or reduce cybercriminal exploitation of friendly critical information. About this context, the cryptography is really important because is the practice and study of techniques for secure storage and communication in the presence of third parties like cybercriminal.

* **Endpoint security**: is an approach to the protection of computer networks that are remotely bridged to client devices. The connection of laptops, tablets, mobile phones and other wireless devices to corporate networks creates attack paths for security threats. It attempts to ensure that such devices follow a definite level of compliance to standards.

* **Network security**: consists of the policies and practices adopted to prevent and monitor unauthorized access, misuse, modification, or denial of a computer network and network accessible resources

* **Data Leakage Prevention:** are measures taken to detect potential data breaches/data ex-filtration transmissions and prevents them by monitoring, detecting and blocking sensitive data while in-use (endpoint actions), in-motion (network traffic), and at-rest (data storage)

* **Recovery protocols:** are process of salvaging inaccessible, lost, corrupted or formatted data from device, when the data stored in them cannot be accessed in a normal way.

In addition to two more transversal points such as:

* Security governance: Governance is the process of managing, directing, controlling, and influencing workplace security decisions, actions, and behaviors.

* Security awareness: is improve the knowledge and attitude members of an organization possess regarding the protection of data assets of BBVA.

![][image23]

Each of these points is briefly explained below and some technologies related are named:

## **3.6 @Employee** {#3.6-@employee}

@Employee product offer tools and techniques have a holistic vision of workplace.

Employee playbook define these 5 stages in which it helps product managers to deliver workplace UX.

* Understanding  
* Ideation  
* Prototyping  
* Evaluation  
* Deployment/Adoption

### **Understanding** {#understanding}

In the early stages of product definition there are tools like:

- Research  
- Surveys  
- Interviews  
- Empathy Maps  
- Customer Journey

That helps to better understand customer needs and identify the right problem to be solved.

For example: every 6-months a global survey is launched to measure workplace satisfaction and identify pain points.

Another example is the set of interviews conducted to identify Linux user’s needs.

### **Ideation** {#ideation}

After identifying and understanding the problem we move  through an ideation phase in which we use tools like

* Key Facts  
* What if...?  
* 5 why’s?  
* Insights  
* Brainstorming  
* Value proposition canvas  
* Principles of design  
* Customer Journey

That helps to generate ideas (solutions) and their impact in the customer journey.

### **Prototyping** {#prototyping}

In this stage it’s critical to finds ways to test our assumptions very quickly.

Techniques like

* Bodystorming  
* Storyboards  
* Wireframes  
* Model

Allow us to do quick and cheap test in from of the final users and learn from them.

Prototyping and evaluation are part of an iterative process. We start with a cheap prototype (usually in paper) to get instant user feedback.

### **Evaluation** {#evaluation}

This is the final phase before start delivering a product. Test are more accurate and also covers end to end processes.

* User test  
* Interactive prototypes  
* Proof of Concept (PoC)  
* Experience test  
* Hypothesis matrix  
* Final conclusion

This is the most important phase in our playbook. It’s the moment in which we get user’s feedback and must interpret it to adapt our design.

It’s important to select the testers properly as their feedback will have a direct impact in product design.

We also use this tests to identify communication or training needs that help us to plan the final phase.

### **Deployment/Adoption** {#deployment/adoption}

Before launching a workplace product there are many thing that we take into account to ensure it is adopted and delivers a pleasant experience.

An adoption plan must include communication actions and training materials if necessary.

These training material can vary from document to videos and even training session with our PMs.

As any other deployment a support plan must be in place to ensure employees has a feedback channel.

Once deployed there should be operational KPIs but also experience KPIs. To obtain the experience we recommend to launch surveys if possible embedded into workplace processes.

# **5\.  Architectural Decisions** {#5.-architectural-decisions}

All of our designs pursue these transformation objectives

* From isolated technologies designed with IT criteria to packaged products designed to provide a good UX  
* From local & vertical support to global & unique support  
* From local & vertical suppliers to global & strategic suppliers with cross vision  
* From workplace spend included in IT budget to workplace spend charged back to BUs as an OPEX (per employee)  
* From a tactical orientation to data & performance orientation  
* From a physical workplace (a desk) to a virtual workplace (anytime, anywhere, any device)  
* From asking every time you need something (support, video call,...) to do most things on your own
